---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-attentive';
const title = 'Yotpo Email & SMS vs Attentive for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Yotpo Email & SMS vs Attentive for Shopify — reviews-loyalty suite messaging vs enterprise SMS scale, retail capture, and procurement-driven stack decisions.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Yotpo Email & SMS or Attentive better for Shopify SMS?',
    answer: 'Attentive targets enterprise and omnichannel retail — broader integrations, larger send infrastructure, multi-brand governance, and account teams. Yotpo Email & SMS fits Shopify DTC merchants invested in reviews and loyalty who want email and SMS unified with UGC context. Choose Attentive when legal, procurement, or parent-company standards require enterprise SMS. Choose Yotpo when suite consolidation around trust loops matters more than enterprise SLAs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Attentive replace Yotpo Email & SMS entirely?',
    answer: 'Attentive replaces Yotpo SMS for enterprise text programs but does not replace Yotpo native review-request sequencing or loyalty earn email. Many portfolio brands run Attentive for SMS governance while Yotpo owns Reviews, Loyalty, and lifecycle email — or migrate email to Klaviyo while keeping Yotpo for UGC display. Full replacement requires explicit trigger ownership across platforms.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Yotpo vs Attentive pricing compare?',
    answer: 'Yotpo uses modular contract pricing — bundle economics when Reviews and Loyalty are active. Attentive typically contracts on annual minimums with CPM-style economics — better negotiated at high volume, expensive for brands that miss commit tiers. A 60k-subscriber flash sale models differently on each; enterprise Attentive commits favor high-volume omnichannel retailers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has stronger compliance and governance tooling?',
    answer: 'Attentive adds enterprise audit trails, role-based access, and legal review workflows for multi-brand portfolios. Yotpo offers solid DTC compliance within suite context but not franchise-grade governance. High litigation risk or multi-brand structures favor Attentive; single-brand Shopify DTC with Yotpo Reviews often prefers suite consolidation over enterprise SMS overhead.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy with Yotpo or Attentive?',
    answer: 'Neither platform alone covers strategic email lifecycle for all merchants. Sequenzy offers guided email playbooks with pay-per-email economics — pair with Attentive when SMS is enterprise-owned and email lives elsewhere, or with Yotpo when suite email needs strategic guidance without canvas complexity. Sequenzy does not replace Attentive governance or Yotpo review loops.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles retail plus ecommerce SMS better?',
    answer: 'Attentive invests in in-store QR capture, franchise compliance, and portfolio reporting for omnichannel brands. Yotpo SMS is Shopify-centric — strong for DTC post-purchase and loyalty text, weaker for mall-to-mobile capture at enterprise scale. Outdoor gear retailers with physical stores often lean Attentive; DTC-only board game shops on Yotpo Reviews lean Yotpo suite.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Yotpo SMS depth trail Attentive at enterprise scale?',
    answer: 'Yes for enterprise SMS programs — approval chains, multi-brand suppression, and retail capture favor Attentive. Yotpo SMS is adequate for loyalty earn reminders, cart recovery, and moderate broadcasts when suite consolidation with Reviews and Loyalty is the primary goal.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Run in-store QR opt-in if retail exists, flash broadcast to 50k+ subs with approval workflow, post-purchase review coordination, and multi-brand suppression if applicable. Attentive should prove enterprise reporting and governance if that is your requirement. Yotpo should prove suite UGC and loyalty context if Reviews is live. If neither applies, compare total cost at actual send volume.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Yotpo Email & SMS vs Attentive</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Yotpo Email & SMS vs Attentive for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Suite trust loops versus enterprise SMS infrastructure. Yotpo Email & SMS bundles lifecycle messaging with reviews and loyalty when those modules anchor your retention strategy. Attentive targets portfolio brands and omnichannel retailers who need governance, SLAs, and scale beyond DTC-native tooling. We evaluated both through a multi-location outdoor gear brand migrating from Yotpo SMS to Attentive for parent-company procurement, a board game DTC staying on Yotpo suite because UGC post-purchase was non-negotiable, and a camping equipment retailer that overpaid for Attentive features tied to retail stores they did not operate.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Enterprise SMS scale', tool: 'Attentive', reason: 'Multi-brand governance, SLAs, and retail capture.' },
            { label: 'Reviews + loyalty suite', tool: 'Yotpo', reason: 'Native UGC and points in email and SMS together.' },
            { label: 'Retail + ecommerce', tool: 'Attentive', reason: 'In-store QR and franchise compliance workflows.' },
            { label: 'Shopify DTC consolidation', tool: 'Yotpo', reason: 'One vendor when Reviews or Loyalty already live.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Email lifecycle layer when SMS is enterprise-owned elsewhere.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Yotpo Email & SMS</th><th>Attentive</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Reviews/loyalty suite merchants</td><td>Enterprise omnichannel SMS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Bundle-dependent pricing</td><td>Annual contract / minimums</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Yotpo contract tiers</td><td>CPM-style with commits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Email depth</td><td>Full lifecycle + UGC</td><td>Not primary — SMS-first</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Retail capture</td><td>Limited</td><td>Core enterprise strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Reviews integration</td><td>Native</td><td>Via coordination</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Compliance</td><td>DTC suite guardrails</td><td>Enterprise audit and governance</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical merchant</td><td>$500k–$15M Shopify DTC</td><td>$10M+ multi-channel / portfolio</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS and Attentive sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Yotpo Email & SMS is optimized when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Attentive is optimized when you run high-volume SMS with dedicated program ownership. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Memorial Day camping spike: camping equipment merchant retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The camping equipment merchant does 1,350 orders/mo at roughly $78k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows tent-capacity quizzes and family car-camping segments, which means email must handle trip-season browse recovery on mobile PDPs before cart before Memorial Day camping spike — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Attentive remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Roast-date math is per-SKU, not per-customer average. Coffee subscribers on pause and wholesale sample recipients needed different clocks than retail tin buyers. Per-product replenishment logic separated natural reorder from discount-trained reorder. For camping equipment merchant specifically, route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day camping spike becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Pottery Studio: class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets</h2>
        <p>
          The pottery studio does 480 orders/mo at roughly $31k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets, which means email must handle kiln-care post-purchase and holiday gift exclusions before holiday starter-set rush — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Attentive remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For pottery studio specifically, exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday starter-set rush becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How vinyl record shop emails through Record Store Day</h2>
        <p>
          The vinyl record shop does 1,800 orders/mo at roughly $72k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows limited pressings with 200–400 unit runs, which means email must handle VIP drop allocation and grading education before promos before Record Store Day — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Attentive remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Waitlist psychology is not welcome psychology. Pottery class leads needed studio policies and kiln safety; glaze-kit promos on day one felt like bait-and-switch. Branching welcome by signup source prevented the mismatch. For vinyl record shop specifically, suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Record Store Day becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Outdoor Gear Retailer ($112k/mo) — merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents</h2>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear retailer does 2,400 orders/mo at roughly $112k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows layering guides and ultralight segment tags, which means email must handle Memorial Day tent promos only after education sends before Memorial Day sale week — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Attentive reduced preview-time surprises because enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For outdoor gear retailer specifically, merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day sale week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before GB close deadlines: mechanical keyboard vendor retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The mechanical keyboard vendor does 940 orders/mo at roughly $58k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits, which means email must handle GB close suppression and switch-type education across five PDPs before GB close deadlines — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Attentive reduced preview-time surprises because enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For mechanical keyboard vendor specifically, halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise GB close deadlines becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Board Game Store: pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Attentive contributes enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Attentive remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Tool friction where Yotpo Email & SMS and Attentive diverge on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS shines when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Its friction shows when you only need email without UGC or points. Attentive shines when you run high-volume SMS with dedicated program ownership. Its friction shows when you are under 800 orders monthly with thin SMS ROI. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Yotpo Email & SMS (modular plans by product) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Attentive (custom enterprise packages) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Yotpo Email & SMS and Attentive both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Yotpo Email & SMS punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Attentive, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Yotpo Email & SMS if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack</li>
          <li>You will use reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite weekly</li>
          <li>Modular plans by product fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Yotpo Email & SMS without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Yotpo Email & SMS for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Attentive if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You run high-volume sms with dedicated program ownership</li>
          <li>You will use enterprise SMS acquisition and managed growth weekly</li>
          <li>Custom enterprise packages fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Attentive without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Attentive migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS is the better Shopify email tool when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Attentive is the better Shopify email tool when you run high-volume SMS with dedicated program ownership. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/postscript-vs-attentive">Postscript vs Attentive</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-postscript">Yotpo vs Postscript</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-attentive">Omnisend vs Attentive</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/camping">Email tools for camping stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Yotpo Email & SMS vs Attentive FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
